title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1903 Pocket Hammerless 32 Caliber - 1921
postcontent:
Colt 1903 32 cal
Colt Model 1903 32 cal
Colt 32
Colt 1921
Colt Pocket 32
Colt Hammerless 32
Colt 1903 32 cal
Colt Model 1903 32 cal

This is a Colt Model 1903 "Hammerless" Pocket .32 caliber. The serial number is 383800, which puts its manufacture date in 1921.  It was in the first 6500 of over 32,000 made that year.  

It is certainly a valuable collector’s piece, but because of its size, the fact that it is in perfect working condition and that it was specifically designed to carry in a pocket, all make it a perfect weapon for concealed carry with true style.

Original grips are in perfect shape as is the original magazine.

The finish is probably 85% overall. The deterioration of the bluing is most obvious on the top and left top of side of the slide, as shown in the pictures.  Given the included shoulder holster and the way the weapon slides in and out, the visible wear very well may be nothing more than holster wear, but I cannot guarantee it.  On the right side and handle, 98%+ of the original blue remains.  The barrel is clean - with no rust and excellent rifling.  The rest of the weapon is also free of rust.

This weapon is in perfect mechanical shape, and is still very tight.  The action is still very smooth.

As mentioned, I am including the leather shoulder holster.  The leather is real and is in excellent shape.  The weapon is a perfect fit as the picture demonstrates.  There are no loose seams, threads or buckles.  The holster is truly a nice addition for a gun that was originally built for easy concealment.  

This weapon is easily an 8 out of 10.  There is wear externally as indicated but the interior parts are not badly worn and the gun fires everytime. 

Please contact me if you would like to see any other pictures. 

If sold in Colorado and you can get to the North Denver Metro Area (Broomfield) to meet for the sale, the transaction for the weapon must be either cash or certified bank check.  I have a friend with an FFL who can facilitate the background check (Yes – as of July 1, even private sales in CO require a background check.) and transfer.  The fees add up to $15 and my Smith/FFL needs to be paid in cash by the buyer.  

If sold outside of Colorado or you live in Colorado and cannot make it to Denver, locating a local FFL to where I can ship the weapon is the responsibility of the buyer as are the shipping charges.  All fees required to complete this transaction are to be paid by the buyer.  For the sale of the weapon, PayPal, some other 3rd party guarantor or a USPS Money Order is required.  This protects both of us from fraud.

Here is some fun trivia...

First the family story...
The weapon has a fun family history as this is the weapon my Grandfather carried when he started his wholesale jewelers business in 1922.  He may have bought the 32 brand new.  Early on, he carried all the gems and most of the gold from all over the Middle East to India to South Africa and back to the US.  When the depression came, the job became even more dangerous.  So Gramps strapped a snub nosed .38 revolver (which is missing thus far) to his right leg and a 22 short, 7 shot mini revolver to the left leg.  I have the mini revolver.  The nickel is chipped and it has no makings at all.  If you want to see pics, email me.  I might be crazy but early research puts the 22 short as a civil war weapon.  I am happy to say, Gramps never had to draw any of his weapons!

Also, many gangsters of the pre-World War II era favored the Model 1903 because they were relatively small and easily concealed.   It is said that Al Capone kept one in his coat pocket and Bonnie Parker used one to break Clyde Barrow out of jail after smuggling it into the jail by taping it to her thigh.   Bank robber John Dillinger was carrying this model of pistol when he was shot by FBI agents outside the Biograph theater on July 22, 1934, and another famous bank robber, Willie Sutton kept one when was captured by police in Brooklyn on February 18, 1952.

This is really a fun piece full of US history no matter how you slice it.  This weapon will not disappoint the new owner.

$650 OBO  - current best offer is $575

title: For Sale/Trade:  Amazing Doomsday/SHTF preparedness package for sale
postcontent:
Scared that the world is going to end? Do you fear anarchy, chaos, death, and destruction? Would you be caught with your pants around your ankles is a Katrina-type disaster happened?

Well fear no more! This package will have you prepared for anything that comes your way, and will provide you and your loved ones safety as you get out of the city and head to greener pastures. It provides offense, defense, AND mobility.

First is a DPMS rifle package. Rifle is VERY far from stock, has had some work done to it and a lot added on. I am the original owner of the rifle. It's had around 300-400 rounds through it without a single issue (loves cheaper steel cased ammo as much as high end match grade!), and has been meticulously maintained.

Upgrades:
-Trigger smoothed and tweaked by a gunsmith
- MIAD grip in FDE
-ACS stock in FDE
-FAB Defense mag well grip
-MBUS gen 2 FDE
-RVG in FDE
-Eotech 512 with box
-Primary Arms 3x magnifier with flip mount (had windage and elevation adjustment knobs)
-BCM low profile gas block
-extended charging handle
-Noveske NSR 13.5 free float rail
-Noveske hand stop
-Troy battle lever
-Accuwedge
-Magpul sling mount on rail

Comes with factory flash hider, back-threaded mock suppressor, and a Solvent Trapper. Also comes with 1 FDE Pmag, 1 windowed blk Pmag, 2 nonwindowed Pmags, and 1 PSA steel mag.
Package includes rifle, mags, 4 mag pouch, and 950 rounds of .223, most is nice steel cased, but 80 rounds are hollow points, 30 rounds are steel penetrator, and 30 are green tip 5.56.

Next is a Condor plate carrier in FDE, and includes AR500 plates for the front and back. The plates will stop multiple rounds of .308, and is coated to prevent round fragmentation and spalling. Carrier is covered front and rear in MOLLE webbing and padded on the inside to add to the comfort of wearing it.

And finally is a 2000 Ford Explorer Limited 4WD/2WD. Has right under 200k miles, it's a Limited so it's got every option offered, automatic, v6, 4WD, PS, PL, PW, cruise control, power sunroof, 6 disc changer, power seats with memory for driver seat, heated seats and mirrors, leather interior (in great shape, only bad spot on driver seat), steering wheel had controls for radio, thermostat and cruise control, center console display, full sized spare, like I said its got every option, runs and drives fine. Windshield got vandalized and needs replaced (cracked but can still drive and see through it), interior and exterior in good shape. Just had both upper control arms replaced, new tires on front and the rear tires only have about 1k miles on them, and will replace transmission filter before it is sold. Its worth around $3500, but it's not doing any good sitting in my yard, so my loss is your gain.

So close your jaw, clean up your drool, change your panties, and break out your checkbook, because this killer deal will not last long as this price. Asking $3600 for EVERYTHING, and anyone with a brain will see this is worth easily twice that.

Will entertain all trade offers, but mainly interested in high end weapons, especially a KelTec RFB.

title: Want To Buy:  Handguns, rifles, shotguns, black guns, pink and purple
location: Greater Seattle and the State of Washington, Seattle, Washington
postcontent: For those of you wanting to sell your guns a few suggestions. First of all don't bother with anyone who isn't a registered user. If you really need quick cash there are a number of honest brick and mortar dealers, DJ's, Wades, Ben's, Pinto's etc in the Seattle area. They won't pay retail, they can't because they have real businesses with real overhead and they all need to feed their families. If you have a bit of time they also accept consignments. The other route is to try and get as close to retail yourself. For this you need to write a complete description to the best of your ability. Look on gunbroker or guns america for your specific gun to compare, this will take some research. You also need to take GOOD pictures, this isn't easy for most of us, but can be done. Don't use your flash if at all possible, use natural or good artificial lighting. Be realistic, most of us that collect and or shoot competitively do not achieve retail when we go to sell. As an NRA pistol instructor many manufacturers give us significant discounts, just like LE and sometimes better than dealers. CONDITION is everything, especially with a collectible firearm. There's a huge difference between a 90% Gold Cup, or Hi Power and a 98%-99% with the original box and all the goodies. It's not easy to tell a gun in 80% to one in 90% to one that's 95% or greater. Less expensive firearms have a much larger market. $200 to $500 guns sell rather quickly, those that are around a thousand have a smaller audience. Those around $2,000 have a very small audience and those that are priced above that you better list with gunbroker, and be patient. All that being said if you have a nice gun or collection to sell, myself or any member of a good gun club or WAC will try to direct you in the right direction. Good luck and try the local shops or to network with someone that's active in the community.

title: For Sale:  Unfired PWS MK114 MOD 0 with Upgrades
postcontent:
I'm cleaning out my gun safe as I'm learning a new-born is a bit more important than having guns just sitting in a safe.  I picked up this rifle just before I found my son was coming and just never got around to shooting it.  For sale is an unfired Primary Weapons Systems (PWS) MK114 MOD 0 with upgraded trigger and buffer tube.  If you're looking at this rifle, you know exactly what you're getting.  PWS uses a proprietary piston technology which in my opinion is much better than a direct impingement system.  This an original MOD 0 rifle which means there are rails all around the upper as opposed to a MOD 1 version which uses the KeyMod rail system.  Again, my opinion on the two styles is that the MOD 0 may be a little heavier but you can put just about any attachment on the rails without having to purchase additional rails.  Currently, the MOD 1 versions of this rifle cost $1,949 retail (with no upgrades) and take up to 6 months to build/ship.  I'm open to REASONABLE offers but new, this rifle would cost you $2,000+.  This rifle includes:

MBUS Sights

title: For Sale:  HANDGUNS, RIFLES, SHOTGUNS, BLACK, BLUE, YELLOW ??????
postcontent:
First of all there is no requirement for you to be registered on armslist to buy, sell, trade or giveaway.  You may do what you want.  If you have a firearm to sell you don't have to take it to a brick and morter dealer.  They made money off you when you buy in their establishments.  They will make money off you if you try to trade with them. If you sell a firearm for $300 and its worth $1000 its your business, nobody else's  If you are looking to buy a firearm and you are comfortable with the price, person, meet, trade etc... etc... then go ahead and do it.  You are a grown up and you don't have to let all the price police tell you otherwise.  If you list a firearm for $1200 and its not worth $200, you will figure it out when nobody buys it from you.  If you sell a firearm underpriced It will probably sell quickly, if you get what you want for it have you lost out? If the person who bought it from you resells and makes a few bucks, great, two or thee people are happy then.  I have been to a few WAC sponsored gun shows and the prices are, a lot of the time, ridiculous, and the dealers are rude, I don't go to them anymore. This is still a free Country, we are for the most part a free People and we can sell, buy, trade as we like.
Semper Fi, ouh raa, yeehaw, yippie yay!!!!!

Perfect for compact, concealed carry

Metal parts on each gun are forged and machined from billet with utmost precision. Fully hammer-forged barrels enhance accuracy. Corrosion-resistant finishes are either super-hard black Melonite® or classic bead-blasted stainless steel. The Ultra Safety Assurance Trigger System™ guards against accidental discharge by locking the trigger in place until direct rearward pressure is applied. Loaded Chamber Indicator allows the shooter to verify without a doubt, visually or by touch, that there is a round in the chamber. Grip safety allows firing only when the shooter has a firm grip on the pistol. A more pronounced texture on the XD-S ensures your grip is always secure.

A single-position Picatinny rail readily accepts lights, lasers or other pistol accessories. It is one of the only polymer pistols of this size with this feature. The XD-S trigger has a short travel along with a short reset which helps to keep you on target with greater ease for quicker, more accurate follow-up shots. The rear sight on the XD-S is low-profile and holster friendly. Fiber-optic front sight promotes easier and faster target acquisition. Customize your grip with two interchangeable backstraps. Includes rugged carry case, paddle holster, double magazine pouch, two interchangeable backstraps, two magazines, cable lock, bore brush and safety manual.

title: For Sale:  Russian Mosin Nagant M38
postcontent:
I have a Russian Mosin Nagant M38 7.62x54r that is in good condition for sale.  This model is a Carbine and was issued to non-coms, officers and troops in the rear as well as some civilians.  As a Carbine, it does not have a bayonet nor mount.  It is basically the shorter, Carbine version of the 91/30.  Fewer of these around.  There are several manufacturers that make a kit that will allow you to mount a scope without having to drill it out.

I have put at least 300 rounds through it in the last few years and never had a misfire or jam.  I am able to consistently shoot a very small pattern at 100 yds. with just the closed iron sights.  Any farther, and I would need a scope - lol.  True to a lot of Russian weapons, I think you could drag this one through the mud and it would still fire every time.  Also, since these weapons were realistically built for use by a peasant army, it has few parts and can be broken down, cleaned and reassembled in just a few minutes.

I bought this for my older boy with the intent to put a scope on it for hunting mule deer and elk.  I picked through at least 30 Carbines to pick this one out.  When my Dad past away a few years ago, I upgraded my son to Dad's 30-06 so I now have no need for this weapon.

$250 OBO
